  "doc_id": "55418",
  "text": "Loss-to-follow-up ranged from 0.0% to 45.1%. Aprameya et al. identified that distance from nutritional rehabilitation unit (NRU), travelling and food expenses, and loss of daily wages reduced compliance with follow-up visits [CITATION_1] . Two studies found differences in baseline characteristics of children lost-to-follow-up. Losses and intermittent follow-up were more common in children who had been inpatients (p = 0.003) in Khanum et al. [CITATION_2] , and children lostto-follow-up were more likely to be admitted with a smaller MUAC in Somasse et al. [CITATION_3] .",
